Bren2010 wrote:That is a really cool idea. It almost makes me think of Rhapsody or Napster. What I mean is, they could play music on 92.7 like a normal radio station, while broadcasting the song for download on 93.7.But if you're going to download the song anyways, why not just record it normally? =PBut yea, not very practical at all. However it's still a good idea to think about other ways technology can be used. For example, for the longest time people used power outlets to, well, power their devices. But now, with the advent of the X10 protocol, it is possible to send signals over power lines in your home, which can be interpreted by special hardware. This is how home automation is able to turn lights on and off from your computer.
